<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-30T09:27:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-29T20:00:00-05:00" n="578" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d578">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/9751</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Japanese Minister of Foreign Affairs</hi>
                                    (<persName corresp="#p_GBS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Goto</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1918-04-30T10:27:00-04:00" notBefore="1918-04-29T21:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">undated</hi></date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received
                                        April 30, 1918, 10.27 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Charged with the direction of Foreign Affairs, in this Ministry,
                                owing to the regrettable illness and retirement of Viscount
                                    <persName corresp="#p_MI1">Motono</persName>, I need hardly
                                assure you of as firm a determination as ever of this Government to
                                promote and cement in every possible way the relations <pb facs="0739" n="647" xml:id="pg_647"/> of mutual regard and
                                confidence between our two nations, holding implicit faith in the
                                final victory of our common cause to which we are unalterably
                                committed. I am indeed proud of the privilege that is afforded me of
                                associating myself with you in the great task before us.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GBS1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Goto</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>